## When to Restart Sessions

The orchestrator's context window fills up as it delegates work and reads agent reports. After a while it becomes less effective — slower, more likely to forget instructions, more likely to edit files itself instead of delegating.

**Restart after:**
- 3-5 heavy improvement cycles (the sweet spot from experience)
- The orchestrator starts doing work itself instead of delegating
- The orchestrator seems to "forget" rules it was following earlier
- You want to change direction significantly
- The session has been running for 1-2+ hours

**Before restarting:**
> Wrap up this session. Write a summary and update all tracking files.

This ensures the debrief, session-state, CHANGELOG, and IMPROVEMENTS are all current. The next session picks up from these files — nothing is lost.

**After restarting:**
```bash
claude --agent orchestrator
```
> Continue from where we left off. [Optional: new direction]

The orchestrator reads session-state.md, CHANGELOG.md, and IMPROVEMENTS.md to pick up context. You don't need to re-explain what happened.

## Your Role as the Human

The agents handle implementation, testing, review, and coordination. Your job is:

- **Judge quality visually** — For UI work, look at the actual app. For content, read the actual output. Agents can analyze code but can't always judge the end result the way you can.
- **Note preferences** — When you see two approaches (A/B tests, before/after), say which you prefer and why. "I preferred version B because the spacing felt cleaner" is more useful than "looks good."
- **Redirect when needed** — If the team is heading the wrong direction, say so early. "Stop working on X, switch to Y" saves cycles.
- **Make business decisions** — The orchestrator will present options for anything strategic. Your job is to decide, not to implement.
- **Review the debrief** — After every session, read `eval/results/debrief.md`. It tells you what happened, what needs your attention, and what to say next.
- **Check AGENT-IMPROVEMENTS.md periodically** — Agents suggest workflow improvements there. Review them every 3-5 sessions — approve, defer, or reject.
- **Push back** — If something doesn't feel right, say so. The agents are advisors, not authorities.

## Tips

- **You don't need to be specific.** "Make things better" is a valid prompt. The orchestrator figures out what to focus on.
- **Push back.** If the orchestrator proposes something you disagree with, say so. It'll adapt.
- **Redirect mid-session.** "Stop working on X. Switch to Y." works fine.
- **Ask why.** "Why did you choose to focus on that?" forces the orchestrator to justify priorities.
- **Request the scrutinizer.** If things feel stale: "have the scrutinizer challenge everything we've done."
- **Fresh sessions are fine.** After 3-4 heavy cycles, start fresh. The orchestrator picks up from files.
- **Check the debrief.** After every session, read `eval/results/debrief.md` for what happened and what to do next.
